  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it came from lawful sources. \n\nMoney laundering is considered a serious crime because it enables other illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and organized crime, to flourish by integrating illicit funds into the legitimate economy. Laws and regulations are in place globally to combat money laundering, and financial institutions are required to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities. Penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences.",
